    <prp:abstract>Pre-main-sequence multiple systems with unequal mass ratio open tidally-cleared gaps in the disc, exhibiting similar conditions as found during planet formation. Here, we propose ALMA observations on the GW Orionis systems, with is a triple system with an very close equal-mass pair and a low-mass companion that carves a gap in the surounding disc. We traced the orbit of all stellar components over the last 8 years, which allows us to derive the full 3-D orbits. We also resolved the disc structure from sub-AU to tens of AU with mid-infrared interferometry, which making GW Ori arguably the best-constrained PMS system.

The proposed ALMA continuum observations will allow us to resolve the region near the outer edge of the disc gap and to study gap-opening processes under well-defined conditions. Using radiation-hydrodynamic simulations, we will be able to derive fundamental parameters such as the disc viscosity and the magnetisation level. We will study the effect of dust filtration and provide insights on the formation mechanism and dynamical history of the system.</prp:abstract>
